= Chapter 4: The Creeping Silence
\
For the next two weeks, the sounds of construction echoed through Luminos-Vara.

In the very center of the city, a massive plaza was cleared. Hundreds of citizens worked together, pulling heavy ropes and hoisting gigantic blocks of reinforced deepslate into the air. They were building the Grand Gateway—the massive portal frame that matched the one Valen had seen in the Void Temple. It was shaped like a towering rectangle, so large that twenty Wardens could walk through it side-by-side.

Valen was everywhere at once, checking blueprints and helping line the inner edges of the giant frame with redstone and soul sand. Everyone was smiling, dreaming of the endless energy the Echo Crystals would bring.

But away from the bright lights of the central plaza, the city was changing.

It started in the lower drainage tunnels beneath Valen’s workshop. A pair of city maintenance workers were walking through the deepslate corridors, carrying blue soul torches.

"Hey, do you notice how quiet it is down here?" one worker asked, stopping. Usually, the rushing water in the pipes made a loud, echoing roar. But today, the sound was muffled, like they were standing inside a room lined with thick wool blankets.

The second worker lowered his torch toward the stone floor. "What is that?"

Growing out of a stone grate was a thick, dark carpet of midnight-blue material. It looked like soft moss, but it was dotted with tiny, glowing teal specks that twinkled like a trapped galaxy. As the worker spoke, the specks pulsed brightly, catching the sound of his voice.

"It’s fuzzy," the first worker said, reaching down to touch it.

The moment his boot tapped the stone near the growth, a tiny, bone-white block nearby—a Skulk Sensor—suddenly grew two dark tendrils. The tendrils wiggled, sensing the vibration. The sensor let out a sharp, clicking chirp, and a wave of glowing energy rippled through the dark moss, disappearing down the dark tunnel.

"Creepy," the second worker muttered. "Let's report it to the inventors tomorrow. Come on, the festival for the Grand Gateway is about to start."

They hurried away, their footsteps sounding strangely soft. They didn't see that the dark growth—the Skulk—had already climbed up the walls, wrapping its tendrils around the iron pipes.

Up in the Central Plaza, the atmosphere was electric. The Grand Gateway was finally complete. The giant deepslate structure loomed over the crowd, magnificent and intimidating. Flanking the portal were four newly built stone Wardens, their chest crystals humming peacefully, standing at attention to protect the city.

Master Elian stood on a raised platform, gesturing to Valen to come up beside him.

"Citizens of Luminos-Vara!" Elian shouted, his voice echoing off the high cavern ceiling. "Today, we open a permanent door to a bright future! Valen, if you please..."

Valen stepped forward, holding a massive golden tuning fork, specially crafted to resonate with the giant frame. His heart pounded against his ribs. He felt incredibly proud, but as he looked out at the cheering crowd, he noticed something strange.

At the very edge of the plaza, where the shadows met the blue lantern light, the cobblestone streets looked... darker. A few small patches of that strange, velvet-blue moss were creeping out from the alleyways. Valen blinked, wondering if his eyes were playing tricks on him.

"Go ahead, Valen," Elian whispered encouragingly.

Valen shook off his unease. He raised the golden fork and struck a massive iron anvil.

BONGGGGG!

The sound wave was colossal. It rippled through the plaza, vibrating the teeth in Valen's mouth. He pressed the vibrating fork against the base of the Grand Gateway.

Instantly, the redstone and soul sand flared to life. But it didn't just sizzle like Valen's small workshop portal. The giant frame roared. A wave of intense, blinding blue and violet fire erupted across the massive opening, swirling into a terrifyingly beautiful vortex. The wind howled, blowing the hats off citizens' heads.

Through the massive gateway, the Void Temple on the other side became clearly visible. It looked closer now, dark and waiting.

The crowd erupted into cheers, waving their lanterns. The four stone Wardens in the plaza stood tall, their teal hearts glowing in rhythm with the giant portal.

But as the sound of the cheering reached its loudest peak, a deep, rumbling vibration shook the ground. It didn't come from the portal. It came from everywhere beneath their feet.

Down in the dark alleys, in the sewers, and under the houses, the patches of Skulk heard the cheering. They pulsed violently, absorbing the massive sound energy of the city. Deep inside the portal, locked within the dark Void Temple, a massive, ancient entity felt the seal loosen just a little bit more.

The creeping silence was over. The infection had officially begun to wake up.